##############################################

DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGML.pl",
  "unionTables.pl",
  "PGchoicemacros.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl"
);

##############################################

Context("Point");
Context()->parens->set("[" => {type => "Interval", close => "]"});
Context()->parens->set("{" => {type => "Set", close => "}"});
Context()->parens->set("<" => {type => "Vector", close => ">"});

$m=random(-10,-2,1);
$b=random(-10,-1,1);

$x1=random(2,10,1);
$y1=$m*$x1+$b;

$x2=random(-10,-2,1);
$y2=$m*$x2+$b;

$x3=0;
$y3=$m*$x3+$b;

$x4=random(-10,-2,1);
while ($x4==$x2) {$x4=random(-10,-2,1);}
$y4=$m*$x4+$b+random(1,5,1);



($pt[0],$pt[1],$pt[2],$pt[3]) = (Point($x1,$y1),Point($x2,$y2),Point($x3,$y3),Point($x4,$y4));


$mc = new_checkbox_multiple_choice();
$mc -> qa (
"Which of the following ordered pairs are solutions to the given equation? There may be more than
one correct answer.", 
"\( $pt[0]\)$BR",
"\( $pt[1]\)$BR",                
"\( $pt[2]\)$BR",
);
$mc -> extra(
"\( $pt[3]\)$BR",
);

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());
BEGIN_PGML
Consider the equation

    [` y=[$m] x+[$b]`]

[@ $mc -> print_q() @]*

    [@ $mc -> print_a() @]*

END_PGML

##############################################

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 0;

ANS( checkbox_cmp( $mc->correct_ans() ) );

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

We substitute in each ordered pair's [`x`]- and [`y`]-values into the equation [` y=[$m] x+[$b]`], and see whether the resulting equation is true.

In one case, [`([$x4],[$y4])`], we have

    [`\begin{aligned}
    [$y4] & \stackrel{?}{=} [$m]([$x4])+[$b]\\
    [$y4] & \stackrel{?}{=} [$m*$x4]+[$b]\\
    [$y4] & \stackrel{?}{=} [$m*$x4+$b]\\
    \end{aligned}`]

which is a false equation. So [`([$x4],[$y4])`] is not a solution to the given equation.

In each other case, for example with [`([$x1],[$y1])`], we have a true equation:

    [`\begin{aligned}
    [$y1] & \stackrel{?}{=} [$m]([$x1])+[$b]\\
    [$y1] & \stackrel{?}{=} [$m*$x1]+[$b]\\
    [$y1] & \stackrel{?}{=} [$m*$x1+$b]\\
    \end{aligned}`]

So the other three points _are_ solutions.




END_PGML_SOLUTION
ENDDOCUMENT();


